# swim-ui Component Structure

When adding or editing components in `@swimlane/swim-ui`, follow this structure and conventions.

## Per-component layout

Each component lives under `src/components/<name>/`:

- `<name>.component.ts` — main Lit component (reactive properties, template, logic)
- `<name>.styles.ts` — `css` template or style helpers (exported and used in component)
- `<name>-*.enum.ts` — enums for variant/size/state (e.g. `button-state.enum.ts`, `input-types.enum.ts`)
- `index.ts` — re-exports the component and public types

## Shared assets

- **Design tokens**: `src/styles/tokens/` — `colors.ts`, `typography.ts`, `spacing.ts`; import in component styles, do not hardcode values.
- **Base styles**: `src/styles/base.ts` — CSS variables; components use these variables.
- **Utils**: `src/utils/` — e.g. `coerce.ts` for coercion; use for shared logic.

## Technical conventions

- Use **Lit 3.x**: `@customElement`, `@property`, `@state`, `LitElement`, `html`, `css` from `lit`.
- Use **Shadow DOM** and component-scoped styles (no global style leakage).
- **TypeScript**: strict mode; export public types; no `any` for public APIs.
- **Build**: code must be tree-shakeable; each component importable as `@swimlane/swim-ui/<name>`.

## Example

```ts
// src/components/example/example.component.ts
import { LitElement, html, css } from 'lit';
import { customElement, property } from 'lit/decorators.js';
import { exampleStyles } from './example.styles.js';

@customElement('swim-example')
export class SwimExample extends LitElement {
  static styles = exampleStyles;
  @property() label = '';
  render() { return html`<span>${this.label}</span>`; }
}
```
